\pagebreakNum

### Water Elementals
<!-- A favoured companion among mages, human mages in particular, a water elemental is near impossible to discern while underwater. If able, it often attempts to deal with threats by luring them along into the water -- dragging them from there into the murky depths. -->

Amorphous masses of pure spring water, bound in bracers. Floating shards of ice the size of a man, glaring with cold stares. It is said that water elementals take on the fewest known types of all elementals, but this is untrue; the nature of water is shapelessness. Formless and versatile, water is the free-flowing element of change, and its elementals may take whatever form suits them. 

***Ebb and Flow.*** Water is the element of change, calm, and healing, but also of crushing depths, biting cold, and secrets hidden so far down that light may never reach them. Water’s servants, therefore, channel not only the restorative powers of fresh springs, but also the freezing, lashing, pressing force of deep oceans and frigid ice.

***A Spring of Calm.*** Water is seen as the most tranquil of elements, or at least the least volatile. Places significant to it are well known for their healing properties, particularly among shamanistic races. Spirits may similarly manifest in clean rivers, gushing waterfalls, or at the hearts of glaciers, wherever the water is purest. The many seas are the place of water’s greatest raw strength, and spirits of the sea are often far more robust. In places of corruption or filth, the elementals will become sickly and aggressive.

#### Abyssal Maw
Unsurprisingly, this plane is almost entirely underwater. It displays examples of all areas of sea life, from the well-lit shallow coral reefs to the lightless abyssal trenches that crisscross the ocean floor. Buildings are half made of carved stone and shells, and half of bubbles and froth, with windows made simply by supporting water vertically. 

***Elemental Hierarchy.*** The Maw is ruled by Neptulon the Tidehunter, who reigns from the Throne of the Tides. Much like the Firelands, there are a number of lords below him that assist the rule of the Elemental Lord. Unlike the armies of fire, the titles of nobility rarely change hands due to the adaptive nature of the aquatic masters. 

***Hydraxian Waterlords.*** While the other elements are content to help only those that appeal to themselves, water flows more freely, and its elementals are historically the most cooperative with mortals, even high-ranking lieutenants of the Tidehunter. On Azeroth, water’s servants have actively taken part in the defense of the world on multiple occasions, even as the others remained silent. 

***Masses of the Abyssal Maw.*** The denizens of the plane of water are far less rigidly categorised than the other planes, owing to water’s very nature. Those few who take solid shape at all will still only be vaguely humanoid, though some mortal races are closely associated with the plane, such as the sea giants, murlocs and, of course, millions of species of fish. In many ways, these mortal species show far more than the elements the heart of the element of water, as they are the most versatile sorts across the entire multiverse. The Elemental Lord of Water, Neptulon, represents this by seldom taking a solid form, preferring to exist among his element as raging tides, gentle currents and fatherly flows.

\columnbreak

<div style='margin-top:265px;'></div>

